The Higgs Boson Analysis
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has raised a certain appearance last summer, and this for a good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally, it’s the last particle, whose existence has been predicted by the standard model – our best or “at least false” explanation of nature and the behavior of matter – but has not yet been empirically observed.
But for the physicists it is not completely sure that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
Furthermore, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a large physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still a lack of data to be completely sure about it.
However, let’s assume that it’s actually the Higgs, as it seems that there’s only a small risk of lying, and let’s look at what it’s about.
There is in this world a necessarily unnecessary law that causes two objects not to be present at the same time in the same place.
It’s not possible to violate this rule – and don’t try it too strong as you’re going to get hurt.
For even if particle physics is a truly strange world, it turns out that there is also such a law for them: the Pauli’s exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same “quantum state”, with this “state” in general consisting of some of their properties.
Based on this, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens who are called Fermione and who are kindly obedient to the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the Bosons are moving, a bad band of anarchists, to whom nothing is holy - not that principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place at the same time.
According to The Particle Adventure, these bosons are divided into two groups from the Berkeley Laboratories (which is surprisingly amazing): the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power parts" through which the great powers of nature spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
But it must be emphasized here that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as you might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of exceptional banality: the photon or the "light particle", which is the "boat" of the electromagnetic power.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is "interrupted" exactly in that place, about like a steel stone thrown into a shell.
Through this “disruption” a electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) is created, and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons “tender of power”.
more stable field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, has to be "interrupted" to make this boson appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the causer has to reach very high energies, slightly comparable to a frozen roof, whose surface could only be broken by a very large rock.
That’s why a huge particle accelerator like the CERN is needed – the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a range of 27 km! – to reach such energies.
The analogue with the electromagnetic field is again helpful to explain the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, they are not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep itself in the refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do it own a mass, while the others (like the photon) do not own a mass.
For what all of these research can now be "good," Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they serve the review of the standard model (SM), and they also enable physicists to thoroughly examine all deviations between the observations and the predictions of the SM.
By the way, there are many physicists who seem to hope that such deviations will be found, as the smallest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
It must be said that the latter still has great shortcomings, as it does not provide an explanation for the gravity (up!) and the dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (re-up!).
However, such deviations have not been found in the CERN so far.
Effects
The effects of these research on the general population are harder to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there would be no.
By the way, in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell laboratories did not suspect that their work would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the deceased physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who in 1962 developed the first durable laser (the first were pulsted) - has already said that the laser was in the beginning considered a "laboratory play".
Imagine yourself...
In addition, applications can also come from all the instruments that surround the research.
For example, again, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor during his work in optics in 1969.
Although it wasn’t the original purpose, this sensor today serves as the “eye” of all digital cameras around the world and has given it the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you can never really know it.
Palliative Care – The Best Way to Die – Le Devoir
With her committee for “Death in Dignity”, Quebec recently discussed the weak issue of the end of life.
The debate needs to be rebuilt soon, although a draft law is being prepared.
However, there is still a lot to do in this important topic.
Le Devoir has tried to look at this closer.
A few weeks ago Mr. L. still lived alone in his apartment in the Montérégie.
The prostate cancer that caused him had left him a period of two years.
“They gave me five years to live, I’ve managed seven years,” he said half-hearted, in his bed at the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in Beloeil, where he had arrived the previous day.
“But it’s always a shock, you can’t be prepared for it,” he says.
The disease does his work: an immense weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting on the table before a delicious lunch, he resigns to let himself help with the meal.
Courageously, he even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My greatest desire is that you heal my diarrhea because this is humiliating,” he says.
A few hours later, the team found a remedy for this evil.
“Thro our lives we experience a man standing,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at Victor-Gadbois’ home.
Return to childhood is an unacceptable humiliation for some people.
“It depends on the person’s ability to take a step back, he notes.
For, according to the opinion of several people working in palliative care, great events take place in the middle of these feedback.
Patients who are referred to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois all suffer from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage, they will no longer be overwhelmed by the doctors and nurses who take care of them with so-called "healing" care.
For Mrs. A., 89 years old, the worst fear is to die “consciously and through revival.”
But through the illness I really met my children.
“I have good kids,” she added.
“I don’t have any wishes in life anymore,” she says before she accepts to put on a mask to help her breathe.
In the next few days, she is still waiting for a last visit to her son, who comes from Italy.
At Home Victor-Gadbois, a group of volunteers offers body care and food support.
The palliative care is then used when there are no other possibilities.
To make death more pleasant.
In Quebec, 11,700 inhabitants receive a palliative care bed.
This is very little if we take into account that one day we will all die.
Here life continues under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The person who dies is given oral care with brandy or pepsi.
Diabetics no longer have to control their blood sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Yesterday night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer to the feet of the dead.
“We’re helping families and patients equally,” says Nathalie Savard, Director of Nursing.
In the house of Victor-Gadbois there is no day like the other.
In addition to a 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family meeting in the courtyard and is well supported by his headsets while attacking his honor, a 36-year-old man, surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children, dies tragically after he has tried everything to survive.
“For six months, three to five beds have always been documented with cancer patients under the age of 45,” says Dr. Christiane Martel.
53% of the patients sent to Victor-Gadbois home come from their residence, 47% come from the hospital.
Problem of access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. to a care aimed at relieving the suffering of patients when the latter have reached the final stage of their lives, either at home, in the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations, such as the Home Victor-Gadbois and the Society for Home Palliative Care in the Great Montreal Area specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this great insufficiency in Quebec’s health care ensures that several physicians specializing in palliative care face concerns with the adoption of a law regulating death aid and assisted suicide.
Since the month of October, a manifesto has been in circulation, which has been signed by prominent personalities of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe to declare their objection to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the health system of Quebec is not efficient enough to ensure that everyone has the right to high-quality palliative care before accepting to go to death aid.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was 14 days with great pain in emergency receipt without taking measures to relieve them.
I am afraid that the patients want to die only because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients, despite the worst forecasts, forgotten until the last day.
Hélène Richard's survival chances were already minimal when she interrupted a difficult chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I’m going to break the treatment, she replied to me that she’s sorry that I’m giving up the fight, she told me.
She told me I was at the end.
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of the patients who have asked to die thank the care staff that this desire has not occurred after their pain has been relieved by a palliative care team.
But it must be clearly said that palliative care in pain treatment is not omnipotent.
According to Elsie Monereau, head of palliative care of the Montreal large-scale palliative care company, 8% of patients don’t talk to a pain treatment.
At the end of life, therefore, doctors often take back to the terminal sedation, which goes beyond sleeping the patient either sporadically or permanently until the moment of his death.
We can no longer do as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will be increasingly likely to use this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pain is not relieved, all say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean, “I want you to sleep me,” but “I want my pain to be relieved.”
