A few thousand websites accept Bitcoin as a donation or a means of payment.
After the rate of Bitcoin in June 2011 reached a maximum of $30 (23 euros), it fell to $2 five months later, before it has recovered to around $10 today (the rates are listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing impressive compared to the world trade of real currencies or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this in a report on virtual currencies published in October.
It describes Bitcoin as “the virtual currency with the greatest success”, “in competition with the dollar or the euro” and “like the traditional currencies”.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the “credits” that are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes also exchange).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, the trade is controlled and processed by a central authority every time.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are at the same time account holder, auditor, money mediator, as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two email addresses in the form of an email.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of the data related to this transaction is signed electronically through a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the entire network-wide account of public accounts.
The crucial step is to incorporate this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task that starts on the computers, with the winner, which is a kind of preliminary central bankier, having the privilege to add these additional lines.
It is a file decomposition, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unified electronic fingerprint.
The computers “accept” the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole is “destroyed”.
The goal is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many nules at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can easily check whether it is right.
The transaction is thus permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If one user wants to pay for fraud twice very quickly (less than 10 minutes) with the same money, only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other remains unconnected, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that has solved the task receives 50 Bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
Bitcoins in circulation are thus limited to 21 million, but can be shared up to a hundred million points, which leaves a certain spark.
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with any improvement in the computing performance.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites that provide services for Bitcoin were attacked and the Bitcoin deposits were stolen.
“The weakness used does not affect the actual protocol,” assures Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a company for paying with real money and uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports the possibilities of money laundering using this anonymous service.
However, cash also indicates this deficiency.
Important actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
By others such as the blog platform WordPress they are accepted.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizmann Institute in Israel analyzed the bill and showed that 80% of Bitcoin is not in circulation.
In November, a “Mega End Sales” was launched.
“Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged,” said Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, the company that turns bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, strongly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
Its Paytunia system corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but it uses Bitcoin to validate transactions that are thus cheaper.
In addition, the owner manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented with the traders, and the latter does not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just have to specify an address that can be “photographed and recognized” by a phone, says Pierre Noizat, who assures that he has thousands of users.
There is a general trend to be observed in which hierarchical systems are overthinked in favour of stronger horizontal-oriented systems.
“It will take some time to get Bitcoin down, but 2013 could be a turning point,” he predicts.
By the way, the ECB proposes in its report to re-evaluate the various risks that are now considered to be high in the event of a success of this currency.
