The breach of the constitution in Egypt
This is a new poker game by President Mohammed Mursi.
While Egypt remains more than ever divided with regard to the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily gives it the unlimited power, he has decided to put everything on a map.
To surprise everyone, he announced on Wednesday that the Constitutional Assembly will approve its final version the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state had given this plenary two additional months for the completion of his work.
Egypt has now relyed on a preliminary, multi-modified text for almost two years, which weakens institutional stability and leads to a legal confusion.
This new initiative only provided for an even stronger division of the country.
For his opponents, the president holds in his “autocratic delirium” by continuing to “break his word” and “the right goes with his feet.”
On the part of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and to accelerate the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period that forces the brothers to give up their plans to explain to the Egyptians the text section for section.
For the president, it is also a way to recover his public and democratic legitimacy while the protests rise throughout the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American Weekly Time, Mohammed Mursi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote benevolently.
Especially as the Egyptian people are given an ultimatum with this withdrawal to an agreed vote: “Of you vote for my draft or I retain the unlimited authority,” the latter is supposed to take an end after the adoption of the Constitution.
85 majority of the Islamist members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of liberals did not meet the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in the middle of November, they declined because they believe they were unable to put their views into force.
Representatives of human rights organizations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to the decision-making capacity, 11 members, deputy members, were added tomorrow morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that the articles were mostly approved unanimously.
By the way, the commentators found it fun that the only discrepancy of the day ... was expressed at the time for prayer, as some members of the board believed that the hour of the constitutional assembly did not go exactly.
The text, which has been adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which attracted all attention, ultimately remains identical to that of the Constitution of 1971 and states that “the principles of sharia are the main source of law.”
The salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope to replace the "principles" with the "rules", which would have made a more strict application possible.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a proof of their good will and their respect for the other members of the Egyptian society.
“Scientificity” is responded by the liberals, who see it only as a propaganda blow.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place through other articles.
In particular, they have regard to Article 220, which acknowledges the University of Al-Azhar as a advisory function, in particular with regard to the review of compliance with the laws of the Sharia.
According to Egyptian specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because “the people who are asked for a statement have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
You can see the first signs of theocracy.”
The fears of the liberals are also fueled by the fact that the next rector of this university is much less modest than the present.
"There is no specific religious engagement to be recognized.
With this Constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
The majority of the lawyers who worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who are partly trained in the French system,” says Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral paper on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
However, he acknowledges, “that there may be a pluralism with regard to Article 220, as the terms used are derived from the religious vocabulary.
It is referred to the “fiqh” [Islamic jurisprudence, Anm. d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to how competent civil judges are to decide about it.”
In addition to its religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticized due to the extensive powers it gives to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim Brothers argue that these are significantly reduced compared to the former regime.
Another point of dispute: the powers of the army.
In accordance with the desire of the military, the review of the defence budget is not submitted to the Parliament, but to a national defence council.
Likewise, there will be no prohibition of civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights defence associations have demanded.
The latter also share their fears regarding the text they view as a threat to freedom.
The fact of blasphemy will beined, and offenses are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Moreover, no article is more related to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef of Human Rights Watch.
In your opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian president had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect holy places, the noble of the world and a sea from the sun
The promised land combines the glory of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AIF tells you the five main reasons to visit Israel.
Above the Holy Places
Visit the river Jordan, where Jesus was buried.
It is said that everyone who swim in this river receives God’s blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his wonders: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding party, the walking on the water, the breastfeeding of the sea tower and the fishing.
This is where Jesus appeared to His disciples after the resurrection.
Most of the churches are located in Jerusalem.
Believers walk here the path of suffering or the cross path of Jesus Christ (in Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The journey begins at the Roman fortress Antonia, Pretoria, where the court was, and leads through the streets of the Old Town to the tomb church on the mountain of Golgotha, where the crucifixion, the salmon and the tomb of Jesus are located.
Here, according to Christian conception, is the nobility of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands at the place where, according to a Christian legend, the tree grows from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus.
In Jerusalem is also the most holy place of the Jews - the Klagemauer, the remains of a temple that was destroyed by the Romans in the year 70 BC.
Traditionally, people of different religions leave there lists of wishes, which then go into fulfillment.
Take a trip to the height
The ruins of the Fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hiding from enemies that Herod the Great built for his family in the year 25 BC.
They are located on a rocky wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only mountaineers can reach the ruins by their own strength.
Everyone else brings an air railway to this historic summit.
In the north of the country in 1600 to 2040 meters of height is the famous ski area of Hermon, which attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you get there with a shuttlebus.
The skies have a total length of 45 kilometers.
According to an ancient legend, allegedly pagan gods lived on the mountain summit.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
With only one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be given a visit.
The museum is located near the Knesset (Parliament).
There are preserved ancient Qumran manuscripts or scripts from the Dead Sea, found in rocky hills in the Jewish desert, as well as about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibitions.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There is the collection of works of the Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Akko you can visit the museum in Bad Al Basha, which houses several pillars of ancient Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bathers.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenirs stores.
Entrance is free and donations are essentially rejected.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells about one of the most shocking chapters in history.
The most captivating department is the children's monument, built to commemorate the 1.5 million children who were destroyed in concentration camps and gas chambers.
When entering the room, there is complete darkness.
The stars shine.
The names of the children of the Jews and the countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Do something for health
The three main rescue areas of Israel are on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
In each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinaries and oceanaries.
Surprisingly, the Red Sea is swallowed in the winter months as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air is heated to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and it is flooded throughout the year.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus carries even non-sweaters easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is undescribedly beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt) and healing slurry as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes and for the calming of strapasiated nerves.
The Secrets of Ancient Age
These secrets cover the old town of Tel Aviv, namely the city of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city passed the famous sea, which connected Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to the surrender, Noah built his ark just here, and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists enjoy sliding through the narrow streets named by star signs.
Fortuna is to be the legend according to all who touch the walls in the street with their star sign.
In Jaffa, you can encounter newly married couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo termins.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can walk through the Roman Theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusader.
In the Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judah and the residence of the Roman rulers, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theater, evening concerts and operas are presented today.
Merklist for tourists
When you’re traveling to Israel, don’t worry about your poor English skills: about 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money on the trip is preferable not to be taken in euros, but in dollars, which can easily be exchanged in shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekels).
In the city you get mostly by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway and in Haifa the only subway line of the country with six stations that connects the suburb with the capital.
It is precisely a subterranean station.
A ride within the city costs no matter the means of transportation 6 shekels, which is sufficient including climbing for a ride of up to 1.5 hours.
According to the Jewish tradition, the sabbath is celebrated in Israel.
From Friday evening to Saturday sunset, markets and shops are closed, and public transportation is resting.
On Sunday morning the working week begins.
In many cafés, restaurants and hostels, only cocker food is served, which excludes pork, seafood, fish-free, and foods that contain both dairy and meat products.
Instead, you will have the choice between various dishes with hammer and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus pasta, various sauces, fried bowls of peered beans and herbs (falafel) as well as fruits and vegetables.
There are no streaming dogs in the streets of Israeli cities.
For this, there are many well-fooded cats that strike through the streets comfortably and unbeatfully.
In the evening, you can even see them sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
Cats like living places and don’t say no to tastes.
A car rental costs between $37 a day (Hyundai Getz) and $188 (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
The insurance costs $15 a day.
And a bicycle rental costs 15 shekels per day.
Entrance tickets for museums cost at an average of 30 shekels.
in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recreation seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the United States and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118.8 thousand Ukrainian tourists arrived in the promised country, which is a 51% increase compared to the comparison period in 2010, before the visa obligation was cancelled on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" Leads to Moscow: Migrants Save Money for Language
While parliamentarians and lawmakers discuss the benefits of the law on binding speech tests for migrants, criminals already deal with false certificates.
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to make money for the maintenance of the families residing in the home.
On December 1st, a law came into force that requires every working migrant to submit a test that proves knowledge of the Russian language.
Until now, this regulation applies only to migrants who wish to work in the service sector, in the municipal housing and in the retail sector.
However, the tests will be mandatory for all guest workers in the future, according to the Federal Migration Authority.
It is necessary not only to test language, but also to test the Russian history and the foundations of the legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both obtaining and extending the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries in which Russian is the official language.
Also excluded from this law are persons who received their qualifications and diplomas before the dissolution of the USSR in 1991.
Meaning, problem and protection of rights
The entire examination bodies will be under the edge of the Pushkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of International Friendship, the Moscow State University, the St. Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take the tests in all cities; more than 160 corresponding centers have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
On the other hand, before the law came into force, civil lawmakers have repeatedly asked the following question in the press: What does this bring?
What changes does the rule bring about the need to show language skills, both for the Russians and for the guest workers?
First of all, the spokesman of the Migration Authority opposes, it is about reducing the number of forced workers.
"Many now talk about the protection of the rights of workers migrants," said head of the representation of the Federal Migration Authority in Tajikistan, Viktor Sebelew.
However, your rights must be protected before you leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Migrants are faced with problems without work, education, language skills and medical examination.
Sebelew is convinced that a future immigrant without language knowledge will necessarily encounter people with evil intentions, which will put him under the pretext of help in a dark, narrow bar, where he will spend dozens of his same months without food and documents and will make 12 to 14 hours a day.
We get a lot of complaints from our migrants.
“In the home you will be promised the one, and at arrival you will be deceived, their passes will be withdrawn and the promised salary will not be received,” confirms Tolib Schwaripow, head of the head of the workmigration department of the Tadjikistan Migration Authority.
Don’t be foolish boss.
However, many citizens of the Central Asian Republics, who want to make their money in Russia, admit that they don’t only master the language of the destination, but they hardly can express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not their fault as much as the evil: only a few Turkmen, Usbek and Tadjik can afford a reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, but to buy them decent clothes, shoes, and school stuff.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first chance to earn money.
“It’s hard without language knowledge,” they admit.
“You feel humiliated and inferior.”
Civil rights officials emphasize the following important aspect regarding the law.
The test must be carried out only by migrants with legal status.
If you do not have this status, there is no examination and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the host workers continue to stay illegal in Russia.
“Heartly welcome” or “access for unauthorized people is prohibited”
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain an official status in Russia.
The reason is the bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, the language difficulties.
Moreover, legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A false registration can be done quickly and only for one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that our documents are mostly fake and we are not registered, and then there are cases of persecution.
“They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea,” Tadjikistan leader Umed Huschkadamov told reporters.
Don’t be afraid of false papers.
On the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants could be false.
Some false certificates that confirm the completion of the language test have already been captured by employees of the Federal Migration Authority.
The fake papers were printed with a regular color printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get these for free: Every immigrant hoping to save the tests so paid seven thousand rubles for the document.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: this costs a working migrant three thousand rubles.
The fact that the most important immediate task is to protect the system from corruption, so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased, both officials and civil lawmakers agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time that they will get time for a language basic course.
In addition, newcomers without language skills are offered jobs in areas where no active understanding with people is required.
