Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this space authority at a Council of Ministers of the Member States of the European Space Organization ESA. Poland is thus the second member of the former Eastern Block (after the Czech Republic, which became a member of the ESA on 12 November 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with the ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The journey of Poland into space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish space enthusiasts were engaged in spacecraft, and they did not always get to understand it.
I remember, for example, the lecture by A. Šternfeld of December 6, 1933 at the Warsaw Observatory, in which the author presented ideas from his pioneering work "Entry to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (born 1905) left the listeners cold, and after years Šternfeld still remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the REP-Hirsch Prize in 1934 for "Entry to Cosmonautics" founded by Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch.
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important advocate of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky's worldwide recognized contribution to the development of space was honored, among other things, by the fact that one of the craters on the ground-down side of the moon was named after him.
In 1925 a railway drain was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
The author of the draft and the details of this project were unknown.
It is not even clear whether the missile should be used to launch or brake the drainage.
This information comes exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantery began to deal with missile-driven shots.
The research work was conducted by the Institut Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
From the submitted documents it is clear that the research had advanced to the stage of practical tests.
The research was then interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, the design of a photoelectric hunting missile emerged in the special press of Ing. Rohoziński, and in the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" of the author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects concerned the military use of the missile launch.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of missile technology were coordinated by the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Committee Doradczo-Naukowy).
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of activity, its work was terminated from the beginning of the war.
Other articles about space appeared after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Towarzystwo Astronautyczne in the Polish press.
The first mention of this company takes place in 1954 in the November edition of the magazine Problemy, in which four extensive articles are dedicated to spacecraft.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal for the establishment of a space company.
At that time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be anticipated that the research of space would have a future.
At its beginning in 1956, the Polish space company PTA sought to join the 1951 established International Federation of Space, and in fact the PTA became a regular member in the autumn of 1956.
In the following year, the first Chairman of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He was in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the PTA has been significantly involved in the development of the extremely successful meteorological missile (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish missile for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and didn’t weigh 5 kg.
Later a improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and in 1959 the Błędów Desert fleet tests began with the two-level rocket RM-2.
The missile was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another stage of development should already be able to perform real scientific work - the RM-34 missile should reach a airport height of up to 14.5 km and be used for the observation of height winds.
In 1962, however, the further development was stopped.
The successor of the first rocket of the type RM was the Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage missile, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types of this missile were developed (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differ from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A missile had a transport space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B over 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C over 0.62 liters.
The maximum airport height was 37 km for all three types.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a 10 kg utility load to a height of about 60 km.
Then the versions of Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning that Poland joined the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960, which two years later followed the establishment of a national COSPAR committee.
In the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second Intercosmonaut after the Czech Vladimir Remek.
