Some groups heard a loud television program from the neighboring room that had nothing to do with the content. Others heard it at low noise, so it was hardly perceived, while the third group did not hear these noises at all.
The people who took the hardly heard TV said they felt more tired than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating, they couldn't find any reason for this, and wrote their difficulties of tired.
When trying to focus on a difficult or challenging task, disturbance of attention can lead to tiredness, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neurosciences at Guelph University in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, if you do a unique activity - "as searching for defective products on a factory support band, music can disrupt and help you not feel tired."
In fact, as he says, we now know that cracks and cracks, often interpreted as signs of boring, can even fight them by keeping people physically more attentive.
“Studies have shown that children who are allowed to walk around learn more and keep more information than those who are forced to sit,” Professor Fenske said.
We all get bored at some point - my delayed flight, a delayed speaker, a tired film.
But some people get bored more easily than others.
To measure these differences, researchers in the 1980s developed a "scale to disappointment."
On the scale there are statements such as "Many things I have to do are repeated and monotonous" and "I have so many interests that I don't have enough time for everything."
Using such scales, researchers have found that boys get bored more often than girls, says Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida - especially when it comes to the need for more and a greater variety of external stimuli.
But generally, teenagers are a fairly stressed crowd.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day with a pager.
He found that 32% of older adults were tired in school and doing home tasks, while 23% said they were tired when they were not in school.
But only 3% of parents said they felt tired.
Professor Larson says today, 21 years later, he doesn’t know whether the percentage of fatigue has risen or decreased.
However, he is sure that “yours are feeling especially boring,” mainly because children and teenagers have no great influence on their daily course.
So back to my original question: Is fatigue healthy?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, it causes people to take extreme physical risks and fall into gambling or drugs to relieve them – that’s what studies have shown.
On the other hand, many philosophers and authors study the relationship between tiredness and creativity. This opinion is Professor Vodanovich, who has been exploring the topic for more than two decades.
“With fatigue, the brain wants to tell you that you should do something different,” says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at the University of New York.
But the brain doesn’t always know what to do best.
When you’re boring and you’re using this energy to play and cook guitar, you’re happy.
However, though television can give feelings of happiness in the short term, they disappear in the long term.
Whoever gives a iPad to his bored child can bring it away from boredness, but he has not learned to talk or control himself, says Professor Fenske.
And he adds, “self-control passes from one situation to the other.”
The child not only learns to talk, but also gets more self-control in other areas.
I don’t think we should celebrate tiredness.
We should not consider them too critical.
Instead, our goal should be to make us feel comfortable, even away from the constant activity and technology series.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
“It sounds like we have to be bored more often, but boredness is the tortuous, inevitable desire to do something meaningful,” he says.
He believes that people in truth are only looking for a way to turn off and relax.
“In an environment where we are constantly over-stimulated, it’s hard to get busy when the noise is silent.”
