The conclusion of the UNASUR summit without the publication of the statement of Lima
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, which was previously announced and theoretically should be signed by the seven present rulers.
Efe repeatedly attempted to gain access to the document signed at the VI. Ordinary Meeting of the UNASUR State and Government Chiefs. sources in the State and Presidential Chancellor initially that they would deliver it after the closure, but then stated that it would be published on the Peruvian government’s website at a certain time.
When asked about the text, they said that the content was presented by Peru’s President Ollanta Humala in short statements to the press.
The access of journalists to information about the summit was limited at any time.
During the day, in the press room only the image of the presidential meeting was transmitted without sound with the message "private session, limited audio".
The few information circulated among journalists was received by the press spokesman of some of the Unasur governments present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian press spokesman.
The only document that was spread during the day was the list of the participating presidents, which caused discomfort among the hundreds of journalists from different national and international media who demanded more information.
After that, Peru’s Presidential Office sent the media an e-mail with the “final declaration” of the summit, but it was the declaration of Humala and not the official document to conclude the summit.
Last October, Peru was the host of the Third Summit of South America-Arab States (ASPA), and even at this occasion, despite repressive invitation by the press, the so-called statement of Lima, which was previously announced, was not even published.
The official website of the ASPA can be convinced that the document was published last Tuesday.
During the two international meetings, the Peruvian authorities emphasized that the information systems would be available for journalists, but they greatly restricted access to information.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment by the Court of Justice of The Hague that would result in a border conflict between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which begins on Monday in The Hague, in the process that Lima against Santiago initiated to listen to the playoffs of both sides.
“We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are presenting to this International Court,” Humala said along with his Chilean counterpart.
“Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country that adheres to international law, seeks peaceful settlements for disputes, concludes agreements and submits itself to the international courts,” Piñera added and greeted Humala with a handprint in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the IGH took place after Colombia, following a decision on the maritime border with Nicaragua, which it considered a serious mistake, had appealed against the Bogotá Agreement, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from the Unasur since 2011 after the resignation of his president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host President Ollanta Humala opened the talks in the morning and ended the summit shortly after lunchtime in Lima.
The head of state read the final document in which it that 16 decisions were made and the action lines for 31 projects between the South American countries were established over an investment amount of a total of $17 billion.
On the decisions he said that the countries of the Unasur "will take significant steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, with which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He said that measures would be promoted to “boost cooperation in the fight against urban uncertainty and organized cross-country crime, as well as measures to improve access to drugs and the internet at low prices in all regions of South America and to act together and efficiently in case of natural disasters.”
With the crisis in Europe, “economic consolidation (in Latin America) should not take triumphing trails, but should serve to expand our production performance and show a better future to our peoples,” Humala added.
"We have decided to give priority to a series of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial connections in South America and especially in rural and border areas ... and thus unite our countries and open up new forms of economy," the Peruvian president said in a statement.
Among these projects will be five Peruvians who are on the queraches of his territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which are intended to ensure better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the election process in this country will serve for its reintroduction to the Union of South American Nations,” which is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to be an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourhood relations was another aspect that was emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before the start of his participation in the regional meeting that he expected a meeting on Saturday in Mexico with his opponent of Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict with respect after an IGH judgment questioned by Bogotá.
